export const mandate: Scene = new Scene({
  id: 'mandate',
  title: "IX — The Mandate",
  image: "scn_mandate.png",
  text: `Henry's study was cold. The fire had not been laid yet. He stood at the window with his back to me for nearly a minute before he turned.

The man I had sat opposite at dinner was still there, but the manners had fallen away from him. He looked tired now, and older than he had looked downstairs.

He poured two whiskies from the decanter on the side table and pushed one across the desk to me.

"You need not drink it," he said. "But sit down."

I sat.

He remained standing.

"You know my family well enough to understand that I would not ask this lightly."

"No."

"And you know what I am asking."

"I think I do."

"The road from Lowford should be passable by dusk. Once it is, the constables will be sent for. After that, the matter will no longer be in my hands."

He looked down at the glass in his hand.

"Until then, I want you to look. Quietly. The rooms, the people, whatever you think necessary. I do not ask for certainty by evening. I ask for an opinion."

"Private?"

"Private."

"And Doctor Crowe?"

"Crowe will write what he believes he can write."

That was not quite an answer, and he knew it.

"The world will be told what it must be told," he said. "But before I let this become a simple death in a locked room, I should like to know whether it is one."

"And if it is not simple?"

"Then I should like to know that as well."

He drank. I did not.

"You understand this is not for your paper."

"I understand."

"The work is for me. Your fee will be the usual one. Double, if you prefer. I have no wish to bargain with you this morning."

"The usual fee will do."

He nodded once and set the glass down.

"There is one condition. Whatever you find, whoever it touches, you bring it to me first."

I looked at him for a moment.

"That is not a small condition."

"No."

"And you understand what it sounds like."

"I do."

The rain struck the window behind him. He did not look away from me.

At last I said, "To you first. Yes."

"Good."

He turned back to the window.

"Then begin."

He did not see me out. He poured himself another whisky and stood with it in his hand, looking out at the rain. I closed the study door behind me quietly.`,
  onEnter: (s) => {
    s.setFlag('mandate_given');
  },
  choices: [
    { label: 'Begin', next: () => investigation_hub },
  ],
});

export const morning_scream: Scene = new Scene({
  id: 'morning_scream',
  title: "VI — Before Six",
  image: "scn_morning_scream.png",
  text: `I woke to a scream.

A maid's voice, very high, very stupid with shock, breaking off and starting up again. Six in the morning, by the light at the window. Doors opened along the corridor. Feet ran past my door without stopping. A man's voice called a name twice and got no answer.

I was on my feet by the third call. I went out in my shirt and trousers, with my boots half on. The corridor smelled of cold candles and wet wool. Two maids were at the door of the master bedroom, one of them holding the other up by the elbows. The one being held was the one who had screamed. She was not yet twenty. She had a hand to her mouth and the other to the bedroom door frame, as if she did not trust her own legs to keep her up.

Sir Henry came out of the door in a dressing gown the colour of bone. His hair was on end. His hands were turned up before him, palms toward me, as if he had set them down at some point and could not now remember where.

"She is not breathing," he said. "Eleanor. Eleanor is not breathing."

He said it twice. As though the second saying would change the answer.

"Doctor Crowe," I said.

"He has been sent for. Where in God's name is he."

"He will come, Sir Henry."

Crowe came up the corridor behind me with his bag in his hand. He had dressed. He looked at me as he passed and did not speak. He pushed past Sir Henry into the bedroom without ceremony.

I followed.`,
  choices: [
    { label: 'Enter the bedroom', next: () => bedroom_first },
  ],
});

export const retire: Scene = new Scene({
  id: 'retire',
  title: "V — A Storm in the Chimney",
  image: "scn_retire.png",
  text: `My room was at the end of the east corridor. It had a brass bed, two old prints of horses on the wall, and a fire that had almost gone out in the grate. The maid had left a candle, a jug of cold water, and the bed turned down with exact, quiet care.

I undressed slowly. The house had settled for the night, though it was not silent. The wind moved in the chimney. Rain struck the window and ran down the glass in uneven lines. Now and then the curtains stirred with a draught I could not find.

I was tired from the road, the dinner, and the brandy after it. For a little while I stood by the washstand and listened to the weather. Then I put out the candle, lay down, and pulled the blanket to my shoulder.

A few thoughts crossed me before sleep. Sir Henry had looked unwell. The house was colder than I remembered. Someone had closed a window against the rain. None of it arranged itself into anything. It was only the end of a long evening in a strange bed.

Somewhere far off a clock struck twelve. I think I heard it. I did not hear it strike one.`,
  choices: [
    { label: 'Sleep', next: () => morning_scream },
  ],
});

