  character: "clara",
  text: `I found Clara in the morning room at a quarter to ten. The fire had been lit, the curtains drawn back, the tea things laid on a small table by her elbow, but she had not touched any of it. She sat in the chair by the window with her hands twisted in her lap, and a handkerchief torn in half between them. She looked up at me with the white faced courage of a young woman who had decided to be brave about the wrong thing.

"Mr. Ashford."

"Miss Harrow. May I sit?"

"If you must."

I took the chair opposite her, on the other side of the small table. The tea things were between us, in a small unspoken way, which suited us both. I did not move them.

"You have heard, I take it, what has been said about your mother's death."

"I have heard the doctor's account."

"And you accept it."

"I do not know what to accept. I am twenty-one years old and I have never been asked to accept anything that mattered. I do not see why I should be asked now."

She did not look at me as she said it. She looked at the fire. The torn handkerchief in her hands had become four pieces and she had not noticed.

"Miss Harrow. I shall be plain with you. Your father has asked me to make a private inquiry, before the constable arrives this evening. I shall ask a few questions. You may answer them or refuse them as you see fit. I would prefer that you answered them. The constable will ask the same questions with less patience."

"What do you wish to ask."

I considered her. The torn handkerchief. The letter at her cuff, which was still there, by the small lump under the sleeve. The chair she had not got out of since she had come into the room. The cold tea she had not poured.`,
