  character: "thomas",
  text: `I told him the cuffs were not wet because of the horses. I told him what Miss Blake had seen in the gallery at one. I told him I had been to the courtyard, and that the courtyard had not been quite as honest as the household preferred. I told him there were things in his master's chamber that the constable would be invited to look at within the hour. I did not tell him which things. I let him fill the silence with the ones he was carrying.

He looked at the floor for a long minute. He did not weep at first. He stood very still and let me say what I had to say. Then his shoulders came down, in the small way the shoulders of a man come down when a thing he has been holding up for nine hours is at last set on the floor.

"He told me only to keep watch, sir." His voice was lower than it had been. "He said the matter was a small one. He said it was a question of a paper she had. He said he was going to put it back when he had read it. He said she would never know. He swore on his life she would not be harmed."

"You were on the landing all night."

"I was on the landing from half past eleven until one. Then he came out and gave me the wire. He told me he would be twenty minutes. He told me, if anyone came, to say he had been in his chamber the whole night. He came back at half past one. His coat was wet. His face was wet. His hands were wet. He gave me the wire and said the matter was finished. He went into his chamber and shut the door. I heard him at the basin for a while. I heard him in his bed at two. I sat on the chair until five."

He drew a breath that did not come back as easily as it had gone in.

"And the brandy in his father's dressing room."

"That was earlier, sir. At ten. He took it up himself. He told me what to do with the bottle that had been there before, the one Sir Henry had been drinking from. He told me to throw it in the kitchen fire. I did."

"And the medicine."

"At a quarter past nine, sir. When he went in to speak to her. I waited outside. He came out with the flask in his hand. He gave it to me. He told me to take it to his dressing room and bring back the one I had prepared. I did."

His face came apart, then. He did not turn away. He did not wipe his eyes. He stood at the rail and wept without sound, in the way men weep who have not been allowed to weep in front of a master.

"I did not know, sir. I swear before God. I did not know what was in the flask I brought back. He said it was the same. He said he had only watered it down a little. He said she would sleep through the night and a little of the morning. He said she would wake up and the matter would be in the past."

"You will say all of this to the constable."

"I will say all of it, sir. I will say all of it twice if I am asked. I will say it under oath. I will say it on my mother's grave. I would say it on my own."

I left him at the rail. He did not move from it. The cloth he had been carrying was on the gallery floor at his feet, where he had set it down when he had begun to weep, and he did not pick it up.`,
