  id: 'talk_thomas_kitchen',
  image: "char_thomas.jpg.png",
  character: "thomas",
  text: `I went down to the kitchen at half past one and found Thomas sitting on a stool by the range with a cup of tea in his hand, in the small careful way of a servant who has been told to sit and not been able to think of a reason to stand again.

He looked up when I came in. The cook went out of the kitchen by the back door without my having to suggest it.

"Mr. Reid."

"Sir."

"You have left the chair on the landing."

"Mr. Edmund did not need me, sir. He had gone into his chamber. He had said he would not be wanting me until four."

"He had said it in those words."

"In those words, sir."

I considered him a long moment. He was not, I thought, going to be on his feet much longer in any direction.

"Mr. Reid. There is a thing you should consider in the next half hour. I shall not press you about it now. The constables will be at the door before six. The constables will ask you the same questions I have asked you, in a tone that will not be the tone I have used. If you answer them as you answered me at ten o'clock, you will be answering them on your own, without the comfort of having said the thing to anyone first."

He nodded slowly. He did not weep. He looked at the cup of tea in his hand as if he had only just noticed it.

"Sir."

"Yes."

"You will be in the drawing room at four, then."

"I shall be in the drawing room at four."

"If I am to come to it, sir, I should like to come to it before the constables come."

"You may come to it whenever you like, Mr. Reid. I have left the gallery and the morning room and the corridor outside Mr. Edmund's door open to you. I shall not be hard to find."

He nodded again. He looked at the kitchen window. The sky beyond it was the clear bright yellow of an afternoon after a storm.

"Sir."

"Yes."

"I shall come to find you."`,
