export const thomas_dies: Scene = new Scene({
  id: 'thomas_dies',
  image: "scn_thomas_dies.png",
  text: `The maid found him at the foot of the back stair at twelve.

A clean break in the neck. He had been hurrying down with a tray, she said. The tray was beside him, broken on the flags. The silver cup that had been on it had rolled half against the wall. No one had heard him fall.

The back stair on the east side was a steep one. It had been a stair I had never trusted in good weather. The runner had been threadbare on the upper landing for years, and the household had been promising itself a new one for as long as I had known the place. The household had not got around to it.

The cook saw him first, from the kitchen door. She did not scream. She had cooked through three of these houses in her time and had the kitchen sense not to make a noise when a man is on the stair flags. She went up the corridor for the butler. The butler came down. The butler went up for Sir Henry.

I was at the door of the gallery when the butler came past. He did not say what had happened. He did not need to. The look on his face was the look I had seen at six in the morning at the door of the master bedroom.

I went down to the back stair. I had pressed him too slowly, and the household had moved faster than I had.

The body had not been moved. I knelt at the foot of the stair and looked. The neck had broken in the manner a neck breaks when a man does not have the chance to turn his head to take the fall. Whether the threadbare runner alone could account for that, I would leave to a constable with better light than I had. I closed his eyes. They were not surprised. They were the eyes of a man who had been expecting something, perhaps not this, for the last three hours.

I went back up the stair without speaking. The house had begun to gather at the foot of it. I did not speak to any of them.`,
  onEnter: (s) => {
    s.setFlag('thomas_dead');
  },
  choices: [
    { label: 'Return to the gallery', next: () => investigation_hub },
  ],
});

export const time_warning: Scene = new Scene({
  id: 'time_warning',
  image: "paper.png",
  text: `The rain stopped at a quarter past three.

I felt it before I heard it, in the change of pressure in the chimneys and the small slackening of the wind against the windows. I went to the long gallery and stood at the tall window that gave onto the western moor. The cloud was breaking at last. A thin yellow light was finding the heather above Lowford. Within two hours, perhaps less, the lane would be passable to a parish gig. Within three the constables would be at the door.

That was the first true change in the day. Until then the house had been held in place by weather, as much as by death. No one could come easily from Lowford, and no one could leave without making a business of it. Now that was ending.

I stood at the window a little longer and watched the light spread slowly over the moor. Below me, in the court, water still fell from the gutters in long threads. Somewhere in the house a door opened, and a servant's voice carried briefly along the corridor before being cut off again.

The work of the morning had moved into the work of the afternoon. The afternoon would have less patience in it.`,
  onEnter: (s) => {
    s.setFlag('time_critical');
  },
  choices: [
    { label: 'Continue', next: () => investigation_hub },
  ],
});

